### Stochastic Decision Trees

A stochastic tree, denoted as \(T\), is a binary tree where each of its \(b-1\) internal nodes is associated with a soft decision rule. This rule indicates the probability of a particular data point taking the left branch of the tree. In this paper, we focus on decision rules of the form \(P(xi)=(_{i}^{T}X)\). Moreover, we introduce a prior probability measure, denoted as \((,T)\), that encompasses the space of trees \(T\) (defined by splits and decision rules) and the associated leaf parameters \(\). The generative process for the data is divided into two parts:

