The likelihood represents the conditional distribution of \(y_{i}\) given \(x_{i}\), \(T\), and \(\). In our case, it is usually modeled as a Normal distribution. Further details regarding the likelihood and the overall model will be discussed in subsequent sections.

### Likelihood

We associate each of the \(b\) leafs of a stochastic tree \(T\) with a parameter \(:=\{_{1},...,_{b}\}\). Every parameter \(_{i}\) specifies a density over \(\), denoted by \(f(y|_{i})\).1. Throughout, we assume that the features \(x\) are fixed, and that the target variables \(y\) are sampled from a distribution whose parameters stochastically determined by having \(x\) traverse down the tree. In other words, if \(x\) is assigned to leaf \(i\), then \(y\) is sampled from \(f(y|_{i})\). If a feature \(x\) is assigned to leaf node \(i\) with a certain probability, this implies that the likelihood \(p(y|X,T,)\) is a mixture distribution over the densities \(f(y|_{i})\) and is given by

